These two Pannonian legions had been left at Poetovio by Antony (see sec. 2). The seventh legion (the original legion of Antony) was called Galbiana from Galba, whom it accompanied to Rome from Spain on his accession to the principate3 there was another seventh legion, called Claudiana. The thirteenth legion was called Gemina, probably because originally made up of two others. Many of the legions had such special names3 more commonly, however, referring to the provinces in which they were originally stationed, as Germanica, Macedonica, Soc. No less than twenty-six different legions are referred to in the works of Tacitus. —recolil = “colendi causa refovere ’' (Heraeus).
